metadata.name: Nothing Remains #25
metadata.description:
The only time I ever received corporal punishment – something that was still legal in schools during the 1970s – was in Double Maths with Mrs Robinson. The log book spread out before me seemed less appealing than talking with my friends at the back of the classroom, and so it was I found myself, palm outstretched, feeling the whack of Mrs. Robinson's ruler, ten times over. "Math sucks." Or so I thought.

Back then I knew nothing of the beauty that I would later see in Mathematics – something which became apparent as I taught myself to code, especially using Processing.

This work – based on code I've been playing around with since 2009 – is my small homage to that beauty. Originally based on Ulam spirals, I've then played around with that starting formula to create an infinite numbers of patterns using square roots, cosines and modulus. If only they had shown me these possibilities when I was younger I may have avoided the dreaded ruler of Mrs. Robinson.

metadata.name: ylb-mess-A #81
metadata.description:
With colors and shapes reminiscent of childhood LEGO explorations, 'ylb-mess-A' explores the assembly process in reverse, using recursive subdivision to create detailed structures instead of progressively building a complex structure brick by brick. Although the tools I use to explore and create have changed over the years, this piece reminds me of the natural creative curiosity that was instilled in me at an early age, for which I am incredibly grateful.

metadata.name: BRUTALIST MOVEMENT #215
metadata.description:
Inspired and fascinated by Brutalism, Modernism and Bauhaus, I've started to explore the deeper connections of architecture using pixel art in a clean, minimalistic and unique way.

The BRUTALIST MOVEMENT project represents the next step in this process. It's an animated generative experiment that focuses on finding the simplest and fewest components that - when generated randomly - always create structures resembling buildings: from small modern houses through industrial facilities to gigantic brutalist monuments.

This resulted in 4 main components: Base, Extension, Gap and Window. These entities are used randomly to create Blocks that form the final structure. 
The whole process is also strictly accompanied by 4 distinct components to hold colors and to be set by randomly chosen palettes: Sky, Sun, Shadow, Window.

Features consist of a mixture of the above components.

The project is animated to show how the buildings come to life. It's also a nice way to show what's going on in the background, because from time to time a bigger block would surely hide interesting smaller ones :) 

Press these keys:
's' - to download a larger resolution PNG
'n' - to shuffle through the 'depth' of Blocks, aka placing them from front to back and vice versa. This is a nice feature to show structures hidden by others and also a cool way to create iterations inside the iteration - sub-iterations - we can say :)
'r' - to reset the Blocks' depths to default

Please note:
Everything you see is generated, animated and drawn real-time. No layered transparent PNGs, PFP or similar!

Have fun and inspiration!


@cloudnoise © 2022

☁︎

Created with P5.js library.

metadata.name: Breakfast #103
metadata.description:
Breakfast is a real-time generative system for creating complex arrangements of primitive forms. Inspired by suprematism, its aim is to arrange simple and boldly coloured shapes in pleasing ways. Driven by a real-time physics engine, it allows for direct collaboration between artist, audience, and generative system. 

Original artwork by Kelly Milligan (kellymilligan.art) in Titirangi, Auckland, New Zealand - Published November 2021 on fxhash.xyz

Upon sale of final token:
- 20% of proceeds will be donated to Forest & Bird (https://www.forestandbird.org.nz/) for conservation efforts within Aotearoa (New Zealand)
- 5% of proceeds will be sent to @liabru (brm.io) for his work on Matter.js

Controls:
- Save: CMD/CTRL + S - Save as a 4096x4096 still image
- Churn*: C or OPTION/ALT + C to toggle churning and direction
- Gravity*: G to toggle gravity
- Bounce*: B to toggle bounciness
* Exclusive to tokens containing the feature

Notes: 
- Churners move for 15s each minute as an abstract clock, disabled by controls

metadata.name: scratches & circles #73
metadata.description:
first fully coded generative artwork by @ndru_art made with p5.js

project features:
- up to 5 rows of 'scratches' at varying canvas heights & thickness
- scratches generated with random horizontal density and variance
- circles of varying sizes generated within a certain proximity of each row
- 5 different color palettes
- 'narrow scratches' feature defined by rows with a thickness value < 10

minters get 10% of secondary sales

special thanks to Orr Kislev for making his 'sketchy lines' code publicly available

metadata.name: In Due Time #25
metadata.description:
“In Due Time” is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht’s mastery of line and Vittoria’s notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria’s poem for the collection:

“In Due Time”
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

To save a high-resolution image for printing, click “open” under the image on the page for your token, and then hit:

Digits “1” through “9” to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: Impressions of Order #249
metadata.description:
‘Impressions of Order’ is a collection of 300 generative compositions. 

Inspired by 90s ROM cartridges, server farms and future cityscapes this project explores perception and documentation of ‘order’ within complex systems. 

--------------------------------------------------------

This artwork is best enjoyed in high-resolution so that the subtle layering, colour shifts, variation in hard and soft edges, faint impressions of construction, and the various low-probability glitchy events can be fully appreciated. 

By default, the artwork will load in 2K resolution (1400 x 2000 px). It is recommended that you view the work in 4K or 6K to appreciate the finer details. 

The keyboard buttons: “2”, “4”, and “6” can be pressed to change the resolution to 2K, 4K and 6K resolution accordingly. 

To download an image at its current resolution, press the keyboard button “S”.

--------------------------------------------------------

Artwork created with p5.js

@nbswwit
Sept 2022
